{% block head %}Graduating in a pandemic{% endblock %}

{% block content %}
	<p>
		On June 12th 2020 I graduated from High School. Of course we had to follow all of the new regulations to keep it safe, which made it pretty different from the graduation I watched last year. Here is what it was like from my perspective.<br></br>
	 	A few weeks before everyone was required to sign up for a half-hour time slot. The plan was to have 7-10 graduates and families go through at a time, allowing for distancing. About two days before the school district changed it to a single graduation at a time, with stages that each family would move through one at a time.<br></br>
		When we first waled up to the building we were met with a nice short line. I got to talk with a security guard who said some of the most motivational things I've ever heard, which was nice. Towards the front of the line there was large sign reading the numbers 2020, with each number painted separately to match the colors of each of the four local schools. We were given a short time to take pictures in front of the sign, and then moved to the next station, phase, or whatever it should be called. A table located under a small tent outside the building's front doors was where everyone entering the building was required to sign a 'wellness form' indicating that nobody currently had symptoms of the Coronavirus. They checked that each of had masks, as they were required inside the building (mostly, more on that soon). We waited for a few minutes there, until the family in front of us had moved forward, and then we were allowed to enter the foyer and progress onto the next station. On the way in we passed the first of many hand sanitizer dispensers located throughout the stages. Just inside were a few tables where I was given my academic stole and an index card with my name. This is where the process really began to feel like some sort of assembly line, where at each step a small piece of the overall graduation was attached. Up to this point the stations were relatively quick and ended with a minute or so of waiting to move on. They didn't feel significant, especially considering the weight of what this was all supposed to be. I figured that would change as we progressed. After that same short wait, we were pointed to the next room, and shuffled on our way.<br></br>
		This time it was another picture opportunity. There was a nice screen in the back of the room plastered with my school's logo (like the ones they have behind famous people, not sure what they're called). Although this was effectively the same space as the room before, with only a single set of permanently open doors between them, here my family and I were allowed to take off our masks for the pictures. I enjoyed this stop because the few teachers in the room with us did a good job of making it feel like it really was some sort of celebrity photo shoot. We also got to talk a little about how excited I supposedly was. This station actually took longer so there wasn't that awkward wait to let me think about how strange this all was. Once it was over, my family was told to put their masks on, one of the teachers took my index card and we were escorted into the auditorium. Just like that it was time for the big moment.<br></br>
		My family was pointed down a single roped off isle leading right to the front row. I was marched down a ramp to the stage and given all of the instructions required for the ceremony, "Stand on the tape, wait for the principle to finish calling you, walk to the table and take a diploma, don't open it. Stand in the square in the middle of the stage for pictures, then exit". It was one continuous direction fired at me. It almost felt too simple. Was that really all I had to do? They had a whole rehearsal last year, and here I was with an on-route briefing.<br></br>
		I got to the tape on the floor, about 5 feet from the principal's podium and the teacher escorting my handed him my index card. He read it, looked to me, said congratulations, and shuffled some papers. I quickly asked him before he started if the instructions I was given really were that simple, he said yes, but first I had to look at the camera so the photographer could take some pictures. Once the flashes stopped, he started right into his speech. I think the 10 seconds it took for him to read was the only amount of time during my graduation that lasted as long as it should have. I could feel my brain questioning if this was really it. It almost seemed silly that I was trying to look professional in front of a audience of 3 plus a few teachers scattered in the back. I couldn't help but keep thinking back to last year, watching my friends graduation, how different their experience was. I would've liked that experience, but here I was. I heard my name and snapped out of my head. Following the directions as if they were programmed into my brain, I got my diploma and stood right in the middle of the square. This was the most awkward time of the graduation because, besides my natural tendency to be awkward, I didn't know if there was anywhere I was supposed to look or how long I should stand there. I'm still not sure if I did it right, but I waited for my family to take their pictures, and then moved on. Walking past the administrators on stage I got a few offhand congratulations before they went back to their conversation. That was a little disappointing over the normal line of handshakes that is given out, but I was actually surprised to see them there given that there are probably about 500 seniors in my town this year. That's a lot of time to stand on stage for each individual's mini ceremony.<br></br>
		Once I passed them and met back up with my family at the back of the room, the next family started moving in and it was all over. Down a short hallway and out the locked-open front doors. Besides those 10 seconds of speech, it really felt like a blink. Compared to a normal graduation it rightfully could be called a blink considering it was scheduled for 5:00 and completely wrapped up before 5:20. Removing the time taken waiting in line to get into the building, it might not have even lasted a full 10 minutes.<br></br>
		In the end I'm still not fully sure how I feel about all of it. I guess the most I can say is that I'm thankful they found a way to make anything happen. I never was super excited for the whole walking across the stage thing before covid hit, so I'm almost certainly not as emotional about this as many of my peers. There is a lot of things that happened differently this year, and honestly the one I am most disappointed to have missed is my school's moving up ceremony. Unlike graduation, every grade level is there, 6-12, crammed into the gym. The seniors get to sit in chairs right on the court, and slowly every grade level 'moves up'. In the end they declare the seniors graduates, and everyone stands up all excited. Ever since 6th grade I was always looking forward to the time that I would get to be down there, sitting in the middle, finally done. Of course that one never happened, never will. I think it's the equivalent for me to how graduation felt for everyone else. Even though it wasn't fully gone, it's just not the same as you imagine it.
	</p>
